Recap

Linear Models

Linear models attempt to model the relationship between outcomes and predictors using properties of lines. Using the EyeBall Test, we can see that there is a relationship between date of birth, F1, and voicing context.

ay_means <- ay %>%
              group_by(idstring, dob, decade, decade_1960, plt_vclass)%>%
              summarise(F1_n = mean(F1_n))
ay_means %>%
  ggplot(aes(dob, F1_n, color = plt_vclass))+
    geom_point()+
    scale_color_colorblind()+
    theme_minimal()

We can attempt to model this relationship with a few straight lines.

Note:

We dont know what the actual relationship is between these three variables. Just because were fitting a line to the data doesnt mean the relationship is a line.

When fitting any linear model (flat, mixed effects, or generalized) always remember that the interpretation of the intercept and slopes are sensitive to scaling of the predictors, and the choice of reference levels.

ay_lm_simple1 <- lm(F1_n ~ decade + plt_vclass, data = ay_means)
ay_lm_simple2 <- lm(F1_n ~ decade_1960 + plt_vclass, data = ay_means)
rbind(`1900` = coef(ay_lm_simple1), 
      `1960` = coef(ay_lm_simple2))
     (Intercept)      decade plt_vclassay0
1900    1.567577 -0.07549335    -0.6433567
1960    1.114617 -0.07549335    -0.6433567
ay_lm_interaction1 <- lm(F1_n ~ decade * plt_vclass, data = ay_means)
ay_lm_interaction2 <- lm(F1_n ~ decade_1960 * plt_vclass, data = ay_means)
rbind(`1900` = coef(ay_lm_interaction1), 
      `1960` = coef(ay_lm_interaction2))
     (Intercept)      decade plt_vclassay0 decade:plt_vclassay0
1900    1.326564 -0.02127689    -0.1613291           -0.1084329
1960    1.198902 -0.02127689    -0.8119266           -0.1084329

Also remember that the interaction effects are the estimated difference from the solo effect. Always draw out the graph that the coefficients are describing. This is especially important when you have categorical predictors interacting.

When do we use mixed effects?

We use mixed effects models when there are important grouping variables in the data, or variables across which you have made multiple observations. In the case of /ay/, there are some obvious ones:

  • the speaker who spoke the vowel
  • the word type in which the vowel occured

For other kinds of data, there will be other obvious and less obvious grouping factors:

  • participant
  • test item
  • the research asssistant who ran the experiment
  • the day of the week
  • etc.

Why do grouping effects matter?

In a stricty technical sense, the grouping of data points violates the assumption of linear regression that observations are Independent and Identically Distributed (i.i.d.). That is, a collection of data points from the same speaker will be more highly correlated with themselves than data points from another speaker.

But in another important sense, if we ignore that these grouping factors, were going to be over confident in our estimates. The flat models are assuming we are working with a lot of independent data points:

nrow(ay)

[1] 84713

But, there are a lot fewer speakers:

length(unique(ay$idstring))

[1] 326

And a lot fewer word types:

length(unique(ay$word))

[1] 959

When were trying to estimate the effect of decade or duration on /ay/, we need to take into account that were working with ~85,000 tokens drawn from only ~330 speakers and ~960 words. This becomes crucially important when there is imbalance across these grouping factors. Not all speakers, and far from all words were equally sampled.

In fact, 40% of all the /ay/ data came from one word!

ay %>%
  count(word)%>%
  mutate(prop = n/sum(n))%>%
  filter(n == max(n))

And, in fact, theres a lot of reasons to think that the pronoun I might behave differently! Without taking that into account, our estimated effects might wind up being a more accurate model of how I behaves, instead of how the phoneme /ay/ behaves!

What are random effects?

Random effects allow us to do partial pooling of data drawn from our grouping factors. The flat model is complete pooling

It doesnt take into account the fact that the big data pool is drawn sub-pools of speakers.

You could try to model the data using no-pooling.

This approach tries to fit a best fitting model for each speaker, but comes with other complications. Each subset of the data is smaller, meaning we wind up with high uncertainty within each model. Its also the case that the model within each sub-dataset is estimated completely independently of all the others, even though we kind of suspect that that the parameters for each speaker should be related in some way to the other speakers.

Its also the case that we will often have multiple and overlapping pooling factors, meanign this would be a fully generalizable approach.

Mixed effects models allow us to do partial pooling. The parameter predictions for each speaker share information across speakers, making the most of the data structure, while still taking into account the pooling of the data.

What are the assumptions of a mixed effects model?

A mixed effects model assumes that the random effects (that is, the pooling factors) are drawn from a normal distribution. If we think of the fixed effects as the mean (represented by \(\mu\)) of the distribution, the model estimates the standard deviation (represented by \(\sigma\)) of the distributuon.

Placing this assumption on the predicted random effects for each speaker (or other pooling factor), results in shrinkage. That is, for speakers with little data, or extreme estimates under a no-pooling approach, they pull their estimates closer in toward the mean.

How is this assumption violated?

As far as assumptions go, this one will be commonly vilated. Here are a few scenarios:

  • There are subgroups of speakers drawn from normal distributions with different means.
    • Possible fix: include relevant between-groups fixed effects predictors.
  • The response variable a.k.a. the outcome variable a.k.a. dependent variable isnt normally distributed
    • Possible fix: transform your response variable if appropriate.
  • There are subgoups of speakers who are drawn from norma distributions with different standard deviations:
    • Not addressible.

Another aspect of modelling the data that also cant be addressed is that each grouping factor might have its own standard deviation to their data, not just their own mean. This just isnt modelled in LMEs, at least not as modelled in lme4.

Why not just more fixed effects?

If we think speakers might have their own individualized effect of duration on pronunciation, for example, why dont we include a speaker:duration interaction? First, from a practical perspective, this would produce an enormous number of coefficients and would be nearly uninterpretable. Second, it winds up being equivalent to the no-pooling approach.

When cant we use mixed effects?

There are a few scenarios under which we are unable to estimate a random effect. The most clear cut cases are when the nature of the data logically eliminates the possibility of a random effect. Consider the two predictors date of birth" and voicing context. Recall plt_vclass stands for different voicing contexts. Lets look at the data from one sample speaker

sp1 <- ay %>% filter(idstring == idstring[1])

If we make a table of all of the values of dob in this one speakers data, we can see that there is only one unique value:

table(sp1$dob)

1979 
 488

This speaker was born in 1979. As a variable that varies between speakers, it is logically the case that all speakers will only have one date of birth. As such, its impossible to fit a random slope of (dob|idstring), because there is no way for any given individual speaker to have a slope for date of birth.

On the other hand, lets look at a table of unique values of plt_vclass

table(sp1$plt_vclass)

 ay ay0 
395  93

This speaker (and most speakers) produced many words, some of which had /ay/ in a pre-voiceless context, and some of which had /ay/ elsewhere. That means it is possible for each speaker to have an idiosyncractic effect of voicing, meaning we can fit a random slope like (plt_vclass | idstring).

On the other hand, lets look at the data from just one word.

like <- ay %>% filter(word == "LIKE")

If we make a table of unique dates of birth which like appears in, theres very many.

table(like$dob)


1889 1895 1901 1903 1904 1905 1907 1908 1909 1910 1911 1912 1913 1914 1915 1916 1917 1919 
  22   78   27   22   35    9   69   54   69   23   43   21   49   40   49   54  152    5

This is because speakers across many different dates of birth said like. This means were able to fit a random slope like (dob|word).

On the other hand, if we make a table of unique values of the voicing context, we get a different result:

table(like$plt_vclass)


  ay0 
10757

The word like ends in a /k/, which means that all /ay/ tokens that appear in the word like will always be followed by /k/, which is a voiceless consonant. In fact, the voicing context will always be the same within each word, meaning were logically unable to fit a random slope of voicing by word, i.e. (plt_vclass | word).

There are also some circumstances where were not logically prevented from fitting a random effect, but we are practically prevented. For example, suppose we did a reaction time experiment to see how quickly people could grab a ruler that was dropped between their fingers. We did one trial with all participants, then they all had a coffee, then we ran another trial.

For every speaker, we wind up having one difference score (pre and post) to work with. Logically speaking, each participant might have an idiosyncratic effect of coffee on their reaction time. If we had multiple observations from each participant, we could definitely fit a random slope of (coffee|participant). However, in practice, we have only one difference score per person, so the model wouldnt be able to estimate a random slope by speaker.

How do you specify the fixed effects?

Model specification is an area of considerable debate. If you are in a position of not know what any of the effects of the predictors in your model ought to be, then I would suggest that mixed effects modelling is not your most effective first port of call.

Following the recommendations of Gelman & Hill (2006), I would recommend:

  • Include the predictors that are known to have an effect, or have been widely discussed in the literature.
  • Consider including interactions for the predictors that have a large effect.
  • Include predictors directly related the question at hand. You should be fitting models with a purpose.

How do you specify random effects?

There are currently two schools of thought regarding how to specify the random effects structure of a mixed effects model. The first recommends that you fit a Maximal Model. This means that you should fit a model with all possible random slopes and intercepts that are logically possible given the data. The recommendation, in case you get a convergence error,p is to re-fit the model without the covariance structure using the double pipe notation, i.e. (predictors || groups).

A second approach recommends that you fit a Parsimonious Model. Their recommended workflow is to run a principal components analysis on the random effects structure using RePsychLing::rePCA(). If there is too much structure, then they recommend removing the random effects with the lowers variance, comparing models using likelihood ratio tests.

How do I report any of this?

Weve gone over the methods youll need to use, but we havent really discussed in detail how to report them, which is just as crucual a skill to acquire as the ability to fit and understand these models.

Well walk through this with the example of looking at the effect of decade, voicing and duration on /ay/ pronunciation.

Visualize

Every report should begin with a visualization of the phenomena of interest, plotting the rawest data available that is also legible in a graph.

Figure XX. The relationship between Date of Birth and Normalized F1 on /ay/ by voicing context. Each point represents a by-speaker average.

Figure XX. The relationship between vowel duration and normalized F1.

There are a number of things about these graphs that make them a bit different from the rest of the graphs Ive produced so far for this course:

  • Ive renamed the axes so theres readable and people will know whats being plotted even if they havent read the rest of the paper.
  • Ive recoded the plt_vclass variable so that it reads voiceless and else, again to make the graphs more readable.
  • Ive flipped the y axis direction, because this is actually more conventional for vowel plots of this kind.

Description of the data.

The data in this paper is drawn from sociolinguistic interviews with 326 White Philadelphians. In total, this constitutes 84,713 total tokens of /ay/ across 959 word types.

For the purpose of modelling, the predictors were scaled and transformed. Date of birth was centered on 1900 and divided by 10. This was done to give us an estimate of the intercept and solitary effects at the turn of the 20th century. Dividing by 10 gives this predictor the interpetation of the rate of change per decade. Duration was log2 transformed, due to its strong rightward skew, and centered at the median. A base of 2 was chosen for the log transform to give the slope the interpretation of the effect of doubling duration.

Describe the model!

BAD

We fit a mixed effects model with random effects

GOOD

We fit a linear mixed effects model with normalized F1 as the outcome variable, with fixed effects of voicing, decade, and duration and their three way interaction. In the first instance, we fit a maximal random effects structure, which includes random slopes for duration, voicing and their interaction by speaker, and random slopes for duration, decade, and their interaction by word.

It couldnt hurt to include some pseudocode for the model:

norm_F1 ~ decade * duration * voicing + 
    (duration*voicing | speaker) + 
    (decade*duration|word)

Notice that in my pseudocode here I didnt actually write out what the data columns are actually called in my data frame. With the exception of some very standardized data contexts, no one will understand what dur_c means, or what idstring means.

On the point of whether or not you should continue with the maximal model, we can look at the results of rePCA().

Table of the results.

The most important thing that I should hope you take away from this lecture is to please always always always report all of the estimated fixed effects.

  • Please dont just report which effects were significant and which were non-significant.
  • Please dont report just p-values.
  • Please dont just report the estimated effects of the significant effects.

If you are in a situation where you must report p-values for the fixed effects, and you use the lmerTest package to do this, you should include the following info in the table caption of the results with the p-values.

p-values estimated via t-tests using the Satterthwaite approximations to degrees of freedom.

I would also encourage you to report the random effects structures as well, since they can be informative.

Model Comparison

Of specific interest is the interaction between duration and decade, and the three way interaction with voicing. There are no strong pre-existing hypothesis for why the effect of duration should have become strong over the course of the 20th century, so we examined to what degree it improved model fit. In a step-down procedure, we fit another model without the three way interaction, and another without the three way interaction and the two way interaction between duration and decade. We then carried out likelihood ratio tests between these three models, as well as a comparison of AIC and BIC.

The output of my likelihood ratio test looks like this:

The general output from this model comparison isnt so bad, but we need to clean it up a bit to be more human readable.

While the BIC weakly favors the model with no interaction at all, the AIC strongly prefers the model with a duration:decade interaction, as does the significant likelihood ration test. No metrics suggest the three way interaction between duration, decade and voicing are worth the additional model complexity.

Preview of more advanced methods

Just like I walked through non-gausian models at the beginning of the course, here Ill just briefly review some other modelling tools that are out there, just to avoid the symptoms of when you have a hammer, everything looks like a nail.

Nonlinear modelling

Not all relatinships between variables are going to be straight lines!

If you have a good theory for why this data has the shape it does, then you could incorporate that into a restricted model. However, in this instance, we dont have such a hypothesis. For situations like this, the current emerging standard is to fit a Genralized Additive Model, using the mgcv package.

The nice thing about gams is that in addition to fitting non-linear smooths, you can also incorporate random effects. Ill show the syntax and some results, but for a tutorial this one by Jacolien van Rij and this one by Mrton Sskuthy

aw_gam <- bam(diag ~ following_nasal +
                      s(dob, by = following_nasal, bs = 'cs') +
                      s(idstring, bs = 're') +
                      s(word, bs = 're'),
              data = aw_to_mod)

Bayesian & Graphical Modelling

Another avenue to take is to write your own Bayesian Models. I would recommend the book Doing Bayesian Data Analysis: A Tutorial with R, JAGS, and Stan to learn more.

library(rstan)
data{
  int<lower=0> N; //number of observations
  real y[N];      //observed data
  int<lower=0> nspeakers; // number of speakers
  int<lower=0> speaker[nspeakers]; //speaker vector
}
parameters{
  real mu;
  real<lower=0> sigma;
  real speaker_mu[nspeakers];
  real<lower=0> speaker_sigma_scale;
  real<lower=0> speaker_sigma[nspeakers];
}
model{
  real mu_hat[N];
  real sigma_hat[N];
  
  mu ~ normal(0, 10);
  sigma ~ cauchy(0, 20);
  speaker_mu ~ normal(mu, sigma);
  speaker_sigma ~ cauchy(0, speaker_sigma_scale);
  
  for(i in 1:N){
    mu_hat[i] = speaker_mu[i];
    sigma_hat[i] = speaker_sigma[i];
  }
  y ~ normal(mu_hat, sigma_hat);
}

ayT <- ay %>% 
          filter(plt_vclass == "ay0")%>%
          mutate(speaker = as.numeric(factor(idstring)))

ayT_dat <- list(N = length(ayT$F1_n),
                y = ayT$F1_n,
                nspeakers = max(ayT$speaker),
                speaker = ayT$speaker)

ayT_stan <- stan(file = "../sigma_model.stan", 
                 data = ayT_dat,
                 iter = 500,
                 chains = 4,
                 verbose = T)
library(shinystan)
launch_shinystan(ayT_stan)
